      • withDSL

        public SearchParam.Builder withDSL​(@Nonnull
                                   java.lang.String dsl)
        The DSL statement for search. DSL provides a more convenient and idiomatic way to write and manipulate queries. It is in JSON format (passed into builder as String), and an example of DSL statement is as follows. 
           
 {
     "bool": {
         "must": [
             {
                 "term": {
                     "A": [1, 2, 5]
                 }
             },
             {
                 "range": {
                     "B": {"GT": 1, "LT": 100}
                 }
             },
             {
                 "vector": {
                     "Vec": {
                         "topk": 10, "type": "float", "query": list_of_vecs, "params": {"nprobe": 10}
                     }
                 }
             }
         ],
     },
 }

        Note that "vector" must be included in DSL. The "params" in "Vec" is different for different index types. Refer to Milvus documentation for more information about DSL.

        A "type" key must be present in "Vec" field to indicate whether your query vectors are "float" or "binary".

        Parameters:
        dsl - The DSL String in JSON format
        Returns:
        Builder

      • withBinaryEntities

        public SearchParam.Builder withBinaryEntities​(@Nonnull
                                              java.util.Map<java.lang.String,​java.util.List<java.nio.ByteBuffer>> binaryEntities)
        Optional. Default to empty map. Due to the nature of ByteBuffer, it is not feasible to pass binary entities as query vectors in DSL statement. JSON strings cannot be parsed back to List object.

        The map will take user-defined name (placeholder) as the key, and list of query vectors as the value. When building DSL statement, use the placeholder instead of raw entities in "query".

         For example, for float vectors we have
 
   {"topk": 10, "type": "float", "query": vecs, "params": {"nprobe": 10}}
 
 While for binary vectors we have
 
   {"topk": 10, "type": "binary", "query": "placeholder", "params": {"nprobe": 10}}
 
 And in binaryEntities, we have a key-value pair of ("placeholder", vecs).
        Parameters:
        binaryEntities - a Map of placeholders to query binary vectors. If using float data, this builder is not needed.
        Returns:
        Builder

      • withParamsInJson

        public SearchParam.Builder withParamsInJson​(@Nonnull
                                            java.lang.String paramsInJson)
        Optional. Default to empty String. This is to specify the fields you would like Milvus server to return from query results. No field information will be returned if this is not specified. Example: 
           {"fields": ["B", "D"]}
        Parameters:
        paramsInJson - extra parameters in JSON format
        Returns:
        Builder
